{"author":{"id":"eaa688ea0d726436b1ece55a8b9d1b531ea04439eb81761f069a85729bf89eab"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1699286173,"nonce":"WJq7tIcYV3WTqJPLk7QAiRmTr5c=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOAW4Y0s51_KsJ","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5585","origin":"github"},"title":"CI: planemo unable to detect python in conda environment at run time","message":"Related: https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/pull/5519\n\nI'm trying to get this R library to pass tests. They work fine locally via `planemo t sceasy.xml` but fail on the CI.\n\nThe library uses Reticulate.\n\n**Reticulate** \n\n Reticulate is an R library that allows one to interact with Python libraries. \n\n-   It works by [being told which Python to use](https://rstudio.github.io/reticulate/articles/versions.html#providing-hints).\n    -   It does this (in order of discovery) by checking:\n        1.  `RETICULATE_PYTHON` environment variable needs to be set.\n            -   By default, r-reticulate installs its own python to `~/.virtualenvs/r-reticulate/`\n            -   This works fine locally, but fails when run via github actions.\n        2.  `RETICULATE_PYTHON_ENV` path to conda env\n        3.  `use_python()`, `use_virtualenv()`, `use_condaenv()` (with required=TRUE)\n        4.  `VIRTUAL_ENV` is defined\n        5.  a venv, virtualenv, .venv, .virtualenv folder exists in that directory\n        6.  `use_python()`, `use_virtualenv()`,  `use_condaenv()` (with required=FALSE)\n        7.  `RETICULATE_PYTHON_FALLBACK` path to a python binary\n        8.  `r-reticulate` is created in the absence of all\n        9.  `PATH` use system python.\n\n- Ideally, I'd just do something like  \n       `\u003cenvironment_variable name=\"RETICULATE_PYTHON\"\u003e$CONDA_PREFIX/bin/python\u003cenvironment_variable\u003e`  \n  and pass that in, but the conda prefix is not one of the  [reserved variables](https://docs.galaxyproject.org/en/release_20.05/dev/schema.html#reserved-variables) exposed to the developers, mostly because the name (e.g. \"mulled-v2-123456\") is not known until runtime.\n\n-   One can get around this restraint by calling `RETICULATE_PYTHON=\"\\$CONDA_PREFIX\" R myscript` from within the `\u003ccommand\u003e` section, or retrieving the environment variable in R via `Sys.getenv(\"CONDA_PREFIX\")`\n     - This works fine in local tests\n     - This fails miserably in CI\n\n**Why does it fail in CI?**\n\nAfter much probing (apologies if this counts as CI abuse), the conda command on the CI is:\n \n```bash\n/opt/conda/bin/mamba install \\\n   -c conda-forge -c bioconda -c defaults \\\n   r-sceasy=0.0.7 loompy=3.0.6 anndata=0.10.0 python=3.10 r-anndata=0.7.5.4 r-reticulate=1.32.0 \\\n   --strict-channel-priority \\\n   -p /usr/local \\\n    --copy --yes --quiet\n```\nwhich looks like it installs the entire environment to `/usr/local` , and indeed when I `echo \"\\$CONDA_PREFIX\"` it does indeed evaluate to ` \\\"/usr/local\\\"`\n\n- By this logic, the python binary should then be at location `/usr/local/bin/python`, but when I set this (via: `Sys.setenv(\"RETICULATE_PYTHON\"=file.path(Sys.getenv(\"CONDA_PREFIX\", \"bin\", \"python\"))`, it fails with the error:\n\n         Job in error state.. tool_id: sceasy_convert, exit_code: 1, stderr: Loading required package: reticulate\n         Error in normalizePath(conda, winslash = \\\"/\\\", mustWork = TRUE) : \n         path[1]=\\\"# cmd: /opt/conda/bin/mamba install -c conda-forge -c bioconda -c defaults r-sceasy=0.0.7 \n                 loompy=3.0.6 anndata=0.10.0 python=3.10 r-anndata=0.7.5.4 r-reticulate=1.32.0 --strict-channel-priority\n                 -p /usr/local --copy --yes --quiet\\\": No such file or directory \n\n\nThis is a really weird message, since `normalizePath` is just a function in R to get absolute filename of a file, and it's telling me that it can't evaluate the path \"#cmd blah blah entire mamba create script\".\n\nSomehow `$CONDA_PREFIX/bin/python` is being replaced by a mamba command.\n\nHow do I get around this?\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n  \n\n\n- I can only guess that the CONDA_PREFIX, whi\n\n- After much probing","files":null}]}